FBIS4-68197 "jptot021__l94001" JPRS-TOT-94-021-L JPRS Terrorism FOUO 24 May 1994 FBIS TERRORISM REPORT HIGHLIGHTS: 13-19 March FBIS TERRORISM REPORT HIGHLIGHTS: 13-19 March FBIS TERRORISM REPORT HIGHLIGHTS: 13-19 March 11111111 11111111 CSO Editor's Note: The FBIS Terrorism Desk welcomes suscribers' comments and suggestions at (703) 733-5512. Highlights and major incidents in this edition of the FBIS Terrorism Report include: Algeria/Russia Gunmen attacked a busload of Russians en route to the Algiers airport on 18 May, killing three Russians and 11 members of their Algerian military escort. Benin A bomb exploded in the bathroom of the "Le Calao" bar in Cotonou, injuring two foreigners and a Beninese woman. Egypt A "security source" in the Interior Ministry detailed for MENA news agency the successes of 11 raids against various terrorist hideouts. The source's description includes the charges against fundamentalist lawyer Madani, who died while in custody. France/Denmark The "Revolutionary Cell" took credit for bombing a Paris travel agency specializing in trips to Denmark and threatened to continue attacks against Danish interests. The group's statement said that the attack was "to express solidarity with" a Swiss left-winger imprisoned in Denmark for terrorist and criminal activities. Georgia/Armenia On 15 May, a bomb went off at the Armenian Drama Theater in Tbilisi, injuring 16 people. Greece/U.S. A caller for the 17 November group took credit for firing two anti-tank rockets into IBM's Athens office on 17 May. Libya/France LE QUOTIDIEN speculates that the Libyan Foreign Minister's visit to Paris on 14-15 May was related to the downing of a UTA flight in 1989. Palestinians Amman's AL-MAJD newspaper reports that the Palestinian opposition coalition has decided to move its operations to the occupied territories. Philippines The Alex Boncayao Brigade issued a directive to kill leaders of the group loyal to Communist Party head Sison. The National Police director for intelligence said the violence "might commence any day" in Manila. Turkey/Greece HURRIYET newspaper reports that antiterror officials arrested a PKK explosives expert trained by "the Greek secret service" in a camp "close to the border between Germany and the Netherlands." United Kingdom The British government has finished testing a bar-code system for airports to ensure that luggage is matched with a passenger. The government will also install computer-aided X-ray and "sniffer" devices in all airports after 1996.
